{{Infobox Newspaper | name = Eastern Morning News | image = | caption = | type = [[Daily newspaper|Daily]] | format = | foundation = 26 January 1864 (issue 1)<ref name="pub1">{{citation| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=zc6BnY4UQmIC| title =The Cambridge Bibliography of English Literature| first = Joanne|last = Shattock|publisher = Cambridge University Press| year = 2000| at = Newspapers and Magazines – Daily and Weekly Press, p.2893}}</ref> | ceased publication = 8 November 1929<ref name="pub1"/> | price = | owners = | publisher = | editor = | chiefeditor = | assoceditor = | staff = | language = [[English language|English]] | political = Independent | circulation = | headquarters = [[Kingston upon Hull]] | oclc = | ISSN = | website = }} The '''''Eastern Morning News''''' was a [[newspaper]] based in [[Kingston upon Hull]], UK Founded by [[William Saunders (Liberal politician)|William Saunders]] in 1864, it ceased publication in November 1929.
==History== The ''Eastern Morning News'' was founded in 1864 by Liberal politician [[William Saunders (Liberal politician)|William Saunders]], it was Hull's first daily paper.<ref name="pub2">{{harvnb|Lee|1976|loc = pp.138–9; also Table 2. The English Provincial Daily Press 1856–1870, p.275}}</ref> The paper was a substantial and serious publication, independent but with Liberal leanings,<ref name="pub2"/> covering both local and world news, with coverage of finance and shipping, and with editorial comment, intended for an informed or professional audience.<ref>{{citation| url = http://www.hullhistorycentre.org.uk/discover/hull_history_centre/our_collections/sourceguides/newspapers1.aspx| title = History of Hull Newspapers| publisher = [[Hull History Centre]]| accessdate =30 August 2012| at = Part 1: The early years}}</ref>
The launch of the [[BBC]]'s radio news service as well as the [[Great Depression|1930s recession]] contributed to the end of publication of the paper and its Saturday sister publication the ''Hull News'' on 8 November 1929; the publishing company re-focused on the publication of an enlarged edition of the ''Hull Evening News'', which ceased publication in 1930, taken over by a rival; the more financially secure and Conservative biased ''Daily Mail''.<ref>{{citation| url = http://www.hullhistorycentre.org.uk/discover/hull_history_centre/our_collections/source_guides/hull_newspapers_part_2.aspx| title = History of Hull Newspapers| publisher = [[Hull History Centre]]| accessdate =30 August 2012| at = Part 1: The Twentieth Century}}</ref>
==See also== *''[[Western Morning News]]'', covering south-west England, also founded by William Saunders
