[[File:BM 35968 Religious Chronicle.jpg|thumb|240px|L. W. King’s line art for the Religious Chronicle.<ref>{{ cite book | title = Chronicles Concerning Early Babylonian Kings: Vol. 2 Texts and Translations | author = [[Leonard William King|L. W. King]] | publisher = Luzac & Co. | year = 1907 | pages = 157–179 }}</ref>]]

The '''Religious Chronicle''' is an ancient [[Mesopotamia]]n register of portents such as the straying of wild animals into urban areas and extraordinary natural phenomena which presaged the disruptions which interfered with the [[Akitu|Akītu]] or new year festival and the performance of its regular cultic activities which included the transport of the idols of the gods to the city of [[Babylon]] during the tumultuous years of chaos caused by the incursions of [[Arameans|Aramean]] nomads.

==The text==

It seems to have drawn its sources from the [[Protasis (linguistics)|protases]] of omen literature in contrast to the [[Chronicle of Early Kings]] which drew them from their [[Apodosis (linguistics)|apodoses]].<ref>{{ cite book | title = Predicting the past in the ancient Near East : mantic historiography in ancient Mesopotamia, Judah, and the Mediterranean world  | author = Matthew Neujahr | place = Providence, Rhode Island | series = Brown Judaic Studies | year = 2012 | page = 91 }} footnote 57.</ref> The tablet has two columns per side and is in poor condition, with the surface severely abraded and most of the left-hand side (columns I and IV) gone. It may have been part of a series as there is part of a catch-line evident on line 8 of column IV.<ref name=pkb>{{ cite book | title = A political History of Post-Kassite Babylonia, 1158–722 B.C. | author = J. A. Brinkman | publisher = Pontificium Institutum Biblicum | year = 1968 }}</ref>{{rp|17}} It is designated BM 35968 (Sp III, 504) and is held in the [[British Museum]]. Written during the [[Seleucid era]], it was acquired by the Museum from [[Spartali & Co]], sponsors of much of the unofficial tablet gathering in Iraq under [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] jurisdiction, in 1880, and consequently its find spot is uncertain.<ref>{{ cite book | title = Chronicles Concerning Early Babylonian Kings: Vol. 1 Introductory Chapters | author = L. W. King | publisher = Luzac & Co. | year = 1907 | pages = 212–240 }}</ref>

The earliest king to appear in the text is [[Nabu-shum-libur|Nabû-šumu-libūr]] (ca. 1033 – 1026 BC) on line 16 of the first column and the work also name-drops [[Nabû-mukin-apli]] (ca. 978 – 943 BC). The intervening text describes a reign or reigns of up to seventeen years. Only [[Simbar-shipak|Simbar-Šipak]] (ca. 1025 - 1008 BC) and [[Eulmash-shakin-shumi|Eulmaš-šākin-šumi]] (ca. 1004 – 987 BC) reigned so long during this period. The historical era covered was a period of great turmoil.

Column II, in a passage ascribed to Simbar-Šipak's reign,<ref>{{ cite book | title = The Second Dynasty of Isin According to a New King-list Tablet (AS 15) | author = A. Poebel | publisher = Oriental Institute of the University of Chicago | year = 1955 | pages = 23–24 }} n. 80</ref> includes a possible reference to a solar eclipse: “On the twenty-sixth day of the month Sivan, in the seventh year, day turned to night and there was a fire in the sky.” Rowton identified this with May 9, 2012 BC<ref>{{ cite journal | title = Mesopotamian Chronology and the 'Era of Menophres' | author = M. B. Rowton | journal = Iraq | volume = 8 | year = 1946 | jstor = 4199528 | pages = 106–107 }}</ref> although the current chronology places this in his thirteenth year and the absence of an appropriate technical term for the eclipse, such as <small>AN-KU</small><sub>10</sub>, casts doubt on this astronomical identification.<ref name=pkb/>{{rp|68 n.345}}<ref>{{ cite book | title = Historical Eclipses and Earth's Rotation | author = F. Richard Stephenson | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | pages = 143–146 }}</ref>

